\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Can I have your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 W.H. Wilcox.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 And your address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 5 Newcourse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Are you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Widower really. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Do you remember what year it was you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 1924.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Do you remember what year you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 1897.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Born in Buckfastleigh?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Born at Dean. Balmoral way. I came down here when I was three year old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So you lived in Dean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 About three years-.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Then did you come to live in this house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No. Bridge Street. Bridge Street. Not there now, on the side where they - just where you go down - show where the old
 buildings are, over the bridge on the left hand side, that's it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you live there 'til 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I lived there 'til 1924. Yes, I was there at 1918. I was called up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Why did you leave Dean in the first place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Belonged to the - is this r
ecording now - belonged to the - that farmer there and - bit of a fuss with the - come back from market one day and one thing and another and - me eldest sister was in - was working there and - she must have said something, he was, in a bad temper and he 
smacked her face and - she came home, said she wasn't going back there again, of course living in the cottage belonging to the farmer. Threatened to turn us out so we had to find a place in Buckfastleigh, that's why all the family came down here.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have many brothers or sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I had seven sisters and two brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Where did you come amongst those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I'm the seventh. Seventh child, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Can you give me the names?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, I could give you, yes. Yes. Well of course there's -
 one, two, three - three - four sisters gone. Dead. Two brothers dead. There's only - three sisters and myself left. We were - we - we were all born within twenty-five years, all ten children. Yes, all ten children was born within twenty-five years. Do yo
u
 want to know when they died or like up with the ages? Well the eldest when she died was eighty-five. The - next one was - eighty-three I think when she died. Other one seventy-nine when she died. And one killed by accident outside the George. She would b
e - quite - quite - she was - she was the ninth child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How old was your oldest sister or oldest brother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oldest one? Oh - I was born in 1897, she was born in - I should say fifteen years older, the - at the least. Possibly more
 than that, yes. Fifteen years older. Well time the youngest one was born you see some of the oldest sisters went away to service so actually - I can't - can't say ten - all ten children was there at one time you see. From the oldest to the youngest, abou
t twenty-five years difference. And they were - three of them went to Plymouth in service in hotels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Father. He was born in - he was born in 1860.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 He'd be about thirty-seven then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, somewhere like about there. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he come from around this area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Yes, lived here all his life, he got - his people built this house, Wilcox's. Not - not him but his - cousins or - father before him built this house. And I think somehow that - 
Wilcox's in those days they used to call this - alleyway what you go up Cock Hill, but I think it's - Wilcox's built most of those - those houses and the one up there that passes Cedar Crescent belongs to Wilcox, that's the people down the garage, and - t
h
ey always used to - this Crest hill but they always used to call it Cock Hill, and this - all this properties - all these - this house here in front used to belong to Wilcox. Well, to - that's what they said, the Wilcox's had - that's Cock Hill you see, c
all it Cock Hill instead of - Crest Hill.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What did your father do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Father was a - a journeyman mason. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he do that all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well sometimes he was out of work you see when they were in the building, do odd jobs then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he start off as a journeyman mason?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
You have to travel that. Yes. Oh travel all around. Go as far as Salcombe. They go down for the weekend. He'd walk down there you know, in the Monday. They'd walk, there was no transport. Stay there for the week
 and come back, walk back. They used to walk miles in those - those days you see. No transport and same with the - anybody come home from school from Holne they used to come to Buckfastleigh, four mile each way. There was no - no school out there. No tran
sport at all, it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your father have any sort of part time job as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, he - well he had - he worked for - for a few months sawing up wood when -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Doing what then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Just you know sawing up wood for - used to pay threepence a 
hundredweight then that's all. But the money was low in those days you see. In a big family of course it was - no family allowances then, nothing like that. And no - you couldn't sign on the dole then, not 'til 1911 when the National Health come in, and -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Was he ever out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Oh he was out of work at times. And I know one period - I think it was in - just in the - about 1901 or 1902, they had - had seven weeks of frost. He was working at Ashburton then. He used to have to walk from Dean to As
hburton, and for seven weeks he couldn't do nothing, seven weeks of frost, about 1901 or 1902, that's when we were living at Dean. I was told, it's before I could remember, I was too young.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he do this mason job until he died, that wash is main job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well he had the sickness come in the end. He died - he was seventy-nine when he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would that be about 1920?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No. 1980 - 1930, I should say he was born in 1950, just working it out, yes. Yes. He was seventy-nine when he died. H
e had to go for a major operation at Plymouth. For a water complaint.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Do you remember how old your mother was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 My mother would be - I think when the first one was born was - she was nineteen when the oldest sister was born. Sh
e was younger than father. She - she was born about 18 - 1860 I should say, and - I was born in - she must have been twenty-seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 She was about ten years younger than your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Six and a half - six and a half years I think, somewhere like th
at. Yes, younger than father, yes. She was nearly ninety-four when she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 1904?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, nearly ninety-four. Ninety-three and eight months, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 That's not very long ago is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 About twenty years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. She died the same - I think she died the same - same year as my wife. 1954. She died the end of the year so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother come from round here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 She came from Ashburton. Ashburton family, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did she do any jobs before she got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, she worked for a farmer at - at the Combe. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Doing what job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Helping in the house. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did she work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, couldn't with a big family. She went to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did she do any part time jobs or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, 
no they didn't - they didn't used to do it then, no. Not with big families, they didn't - the jobs wasn't going. No, the jobs wasn't going in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What kind of hours did she have to work in service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well - I can't go back to that exactly 
but - they used to sleep in, they - they used - I think they used to sleep in in those days. Yes. Well they used to take - the farmers used to take them on - they had a way to go and they slept in, the same with the boys and - I think, most times they sle
pt in the farms see. So they got their hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Can you remember how many rooms there would be in the house at Dean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I couldn't say about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How about the one here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh at Buckfastleigh, well the - two big bedrooms. Yes. Yes. The boys 
would be in one - sleep in one and the girls in another, yes. But the - I think one of me sisters like used to work for a shop here and she used to - with old - old lady, she used to sleep over there so that made it better. And another one lived at - went
 out to work up Silver Street for a gentleman, she used to sleep there too. 'Course it made it better - easier for others remainder, the remainder what was left. Yes. Oh it was quite big.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have reception rooms or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No. No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did anyone else besides your parents or brothers and sisters live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, no. No, wasn't big enough for that see. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, no lodgers, no. No. No. It was a - it was a hard life, I mean to say money w
as - money was scarce. And I always thought in those days there was only two classes, the rich and the poor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother ever pay anyone to help in the house at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No. No. She was very generous, she would do - stay up 'til - late Saturday
 nights to make a pair of trousers for somebody else children or for - her used to do a lot of sewing and one thing - her was too good hearted in a way, yes. She'd do anything. She was one of those sort that would do anything for anybody. They say, come o
n, will you make a shirt for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
me or make a pair of - little pair of trousers for me, and her used to get at it you know and do it for 'em. Never used to charge nothing. Her was that - that way inclined, so good hearted. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Where would the family washing be done, did she do it at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Did it home, yes, there was no - I - I don't see nobody have any - no laundry people come then, they used to do all their own, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 She never took any in for other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well I - no, I don't t
hink so. Couldn't remember that, no. But the - with all the children she was always very happy you know. She was always in the same mood. I don't say so with father 'cos - of course there wasn't a lot - lot to do for men, coming to - I think there was mor
e
 - going to the pubs in those days you see, they used to be open six in the morning 'til eleven at night and started drinking in the morning and the time the day was over they'd got enough. And weekends you used to see a lot of drunk - you know, a lot of 
drunkards, yes. And fighting and one and thing and another in the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 The women didn't go in the pubs did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No women going in pubs. No. No, never seen a woman in pub, not this - not this side or that side of the - first war you know, no. No we 
never see a woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother or father ever mend or make the family clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
No, he couldn't do that, no. No. One thing about it in those days, shopkeepers and - merchants, they were very generous, as long as - as long as you paid so much every week you could go in the following week. And we used to buy clothes in those days, pack
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
mans come with - from Exeter one came, and you could have a suit of clothes say - put two bob down, two shilling down and - pay so much a week and you could have 
a suit of clothes perhaps for thirty bob in those days. And most boys - used to wear suits of clothes, not odd - no like sports coats in those days, it was always suits. And - I don't think any - any boys - wore long trousers until they were sixteen. Used
 to wear knickerbockers in those days, yes. But - I could never see anybody going to school with long trousers on. No. 'Course they left school at thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would these clothes be new or second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh it would be new, yes, they'd be new. Yes. Y
es. He was very good the packman. Used to come like - carry their bag and box on their backs and one thing and another. But - all - all by train you see, there was no - buses. He was quite good. We used to pay up everything, got their books and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did they come round selling shoes like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
I - I think he did, I think he - of course in those days nobody wore shoes you know, it was all boots. All boots in those days, and the girls used to have the long boots. Yes. Of course and - all the women had was long skirts in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would there be cobblers shops where you could get your boots mended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes, there was cobblers, plenty of - plenty of cobblers, repairers, but most of the boys wore - nail boots you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 They were long lasting were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
They were long lasting, yes, well you - of course the - the - the streets was - was rough in those days. What they used to do in those days, you've heard of the black rock quarry, that stone, lime stone, they used to lay them som
etimes you know, these different size - all one size like, lay it on the streets. And be a whole week before steam roller come along to - roll it in. Of course the roads was rough then And - used to get tremendous lot of dust - of course with that. The co
uncil used to come around in the summer and - in the summer, and - with a house pipe and - all over the streets to keep the dust down. There was none of this tarmac you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your father ever help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Oh when he was at home you see, he was away to work all day, of course - sisters and one thing and another like when they come home from work they used to give - give a helping hand. The sisters used to work in the mill you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he ever do anything like cleaning up or cooking or washing up or things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, I don't think he did. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I suppose with a large family you'd have so many people who could do it that it wasn't necessary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. You'd got sisters you see. Oh mother was a goodworker and used to have good health too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your father do anything like decorating or repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, don't think he did, no, I think - no, I don't think so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he ever dress you or get you undressed for a bath or something like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh he used to do that sometimes, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, I - you see some of the older people they couldn't read or write you know. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 The schools were only just coming in then weren't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Some of the older people never went to school you know. Not the mothers and that. Not that age you know. Not in - not back in - say the 60's or just after the 60's 1860's but lot of them never - never went to school. When they had to sign anyt
hing they just had to put across on it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he ever tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, I don't - I can't - think of that, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes, he - I used to go walks like with him you know. I know whe
n I was in - Newton Abbot in the first world war, I was stationed there with the Second - the Second Fifth Devon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
s, in - 1914, he - he walked from here up to see me at Newton and back on the Sunday afternoon to see me before I went to India. With the regim
ent, with the Second - Second Sixth Regiment - Second Sixth Devon Regiment. Yes, he walked that way. People used to do a lot of walking in those days you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would he ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes, he'd be there, yes. 'Co
urse I know he - when he was - when the Paignton Waterworks were on he - he and his - eldest son, they - they used to work at Paignton Waterworks while they were doing the Paignton Reservoir, you know in - say 1905, 1906 one or the other and they used to 
walk - go out and stay there for a week like,; because come - setting off each day would be a fair - journey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Paignton reservoir was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. Yes, yes. Built that one, yes. He was on from - that one was on 1902 until 1907, that was when he was 
- he was home in June 1907. They worked there the last two years. Yes. And the funny thing about it was that - when he was coming home that Friday night in April 1906 they could see that there was a big fire at Buckfastleigh, they didn't know where 'cos -
 them high rock coming from Holne and coming along. And that was when the mill was on fire, Church's mill was on fire in Chelscourt. It burnt out in April 1906. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Was that the end of that mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 That was the end of it. If they had the money th
en they could have - rebuilt if or course and - and that was - caused a lot of the workers to - push off to America, they had relatives out there. Between 1906 -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 There were no other jobs in the area to go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, there wasn't, not - no, no. And 
- they had friends in America you know and - the - 1906 to 1914 was any amount went to America, in the textile trade in America. And - in those days - if anybody was going away always had to go away by train you know from - Totnes station, used to be sixt
y or seventy down there and - see 'em off - every time. And - 'til we meet again, always - God be with us 'til we meet again, all before they go. Some tears about the eye. That was - that happened from 1906 to 1914.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Was it just that one mill it happened to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Or did it happen in lots of places, people having to go because there was no jobs for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well - several families went out of course and they'd had children in America so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did they ever come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So - a few of 'em
 come back for holidays. But - perhaps they - continued out their field in America, in the textile - in the textile trade, only in the textile trade. That was the pity of it, I believe they employed about fifty up here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were all the towns around here textile towns or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043 Well - they always c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
alled John Bury's of Buckfast was a - Ashburton firm you see, but - Bury's. Yes. But of course there are now other textile came on after - that was after the war. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you ever have any special task 
you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father, there were lots of children, were you given sort of different tasks to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No I don't think so anyway you see you know - 'cos I was very young you see, I was one of the youngest t
here. Yes. But like I say there wasn't very much money about in those days. You see, in the mills - they in the combing department at the mill they was only getting about seventeen shilling a week. And when I went there in 1910 I got - five shilling a wee
k
. Fifty-six hours. And used to get - a sixpenny rise every six months. Well I - I thought I was going to get a little bit more, I went in the Buckfast in 1912 and I got - about eight shilling when I went in there of course and - stayed there for - coal st
rike in 1912 so we - that was shut down I had no - so I came back to the old firm again. And I was getting about eight and six when - when the war broke out, went away camp.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were these wages low to live off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, they were seventeen shillings, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 That would be for a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
At finish, yes, all you're getting in a mill, yes, in combing, yes. The foreman might get a little bit more. But - you see - no paid holidays. You get Easter time, you lose the Good Friday. Then Easter Monday, 
well two weeks you had no wages you see Good Friday and Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You didn't get paid on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Not - not in those days, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 By law you had to have a holiday on Bank Holiday didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 We had the - we had the days off but - not the pay. Not 'til - when we - as I say after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You don't think anyone did anything to help around the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well I got to chop sticks or anything like that or go out and get some sticks and one thing and another and get some wood and
 one thing and another and - saw it up and chop sticks and one thing and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did the older children help the younger children with anything they found difficult, like dressing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, well they used to - like, well, the sister I know - one of
 me sister's used to knit a lot of socks - stockings you know, she used to go into that to save mother money you know. Used to knit all the stockings - stockings. And mother could - make our shirts and one thing and another, you could buy the cloth you kn
ow, like this - the cloth for to make shirts. She very good with a - with a needle. And the sisters used to do a bit of knitting for the socks and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did they ever help you to eat, learn how to eat properly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. Oh used to be taught the table man
ners you know I mean to say and all that. Yes. Of course we had fairly good food, it was common food but - fair amount you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would the younger children help the older ones in any way, you say you were one of the youngest ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. Oh - go errands, yes, you'd go errands, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Oh yes, we should - we'd go - it wasn't too late, I mean those days I don't think any boys was. Not like - not - not like they are at present now. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Who put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Well we - mother would say - say, time to go to bed, and she used to go up like and - but there was no hot bottles in those days. Of course and when you got - I say when I started work well of course I had to be up at half past
 five, you'd be down work by six o'clock then, when I started work. And at that period the funniest part of it was the - mother was in hospital. She had a serious operation and - she was in there for several weeks. Just the same - about the same time as I
 went - you know, when - when I started work, she was in Ashburton hospital in those days. But in those days you had to pay so much. No matter - no matter how poor you was you had to pay something, I think we had to pay half a crown a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Was that regularly or half a crown while she was in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Only - only just while she was in hospital, there was no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What age do you think you'd be when you started putting yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh - oh eight or nine I think, yes, must have been. Sometim
es you feel tired like that you know, I mean to say - quite active, the boys running about you know. Sometimes in the wintertime might go play at football, well you get tired out and one thing and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You'd share the bedroom with the other brothers wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 With other brothers, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You just had the one bed between you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Used to have bed - yes - couple of beds between three of us like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 And all the girls would be in the other room?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Other room, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Where would your parents be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Parents - well of course like I said the - couple of sisters, the elder ones had gone on - gone on to Plymouth like in service in hotels. And two of 'em used to sleep out, one with a - a shop, another one with - another lad
y up the other part of the town so - mother and father would be in one room then us be - us be in the other one you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So the sisters were a lot older than you really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were the boys younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Boys was - one was older and one was younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 The same room we did - when they was all downstairs. Yes. There was no bathroom those days, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have one of these bucket type things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Big bath - big bath, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How often did you have to bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh - when - when we wanted to like, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 There no special bath}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 night or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh no. No, no, no. NA. 'Course as we - us used to go like - down the Dart swimming and down the - at school we had - you
 could go twice - twice a week at school, Tuesdays and Fridays, regular. Yes. And then we had other times you cold go in the Dart swimming about, mother said well - used to do a good bit of swimming and kept ourselves clean that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did it cost anything to go to the baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
No, when we was at school - when we was at school we used to go twice a - twice a week. Tuesdays and Fridays. But - outside the - schooldays, like Tuesday and Fridays, we used to - we got to pay then. But we didn't used to tro
uble about that, we used to go Buckfastleigh mill. Or down the Dart. They used to go down the Dart in those days like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have to have clean clothes on on a special day or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Only Sundays like. Yes. One thing about it, in - in those
 days, nearly everybody went to - went to their church. It's like they was compelled, the parents would always send them, you get in like a chapel or the Wesleyan, the Congregational and the church, Sundays fill up. The children used to go first thing in 
the morning and - they expect you to - they always said a collect for the day. You'd practice that one before you go and - they used to give you a - give you a prize for attendance and I think that was a big thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What kind of prize would you get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
I was just going to show you one. Up there where - Bickerton House, 'course it's all pulled down now but - they used to help the church a lot. And of course the - the living of the church belonged to the Clements and they passed it on to one of the - vi
cars afterwards. But they used to - give a lot of money and one thing and another and - we used to go up there have a tea sometimes, we did up - for the Golden Wedding, went up to Bickerton but - during the first world war it - it was a - a - hostel for o
fficers. But after that it went in decay and it's practically gone. Yes. Clements.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did everyone get a prize or was it just for attendance? Did you have to do anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I think it was mostly for attendance but - yes, I think it's mostly - nea
rly everybody had one out there. To attendance. Of course some of 'em go with two or three year without missing. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh in our house you see. The - 'course sometimes the - the father would be away and perh
aps - perhaps a brother be away to work, he'd take 'em meals you see. Only time you be - perhaps on Sunday. And - like I say the girls went away early in my lifetime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So you weren't together as a big family all the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well I don't - I don't t
hink the - I don't think it's getting - ten all together at one time, I think the eldest one was going on to service in Plymouth at the hotels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What age would they be when they went down there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh - seventeen, eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So they wouldn't go down there straight from school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh no, they worked - they worked in the mill for a little while and then went later. Oh but - I had two sisters work in the Churchill}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5397527\charrsid5841043 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 s mill, when the - you know, the time it burned down, of course it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were they actually in it when it burned down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
No, the fire was in - working ends at five, after - about twenty past six maybe so leave work before that, half past five see. And - they was working at the time, of course when the mill burnt down they had to se
ek other - jobs so - other two had gone previously out of our ones that were in Plymouth. And the - and the third one, she went to - she went into service in the hotels at - Plymouth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were there any occasions when you'd eat in another room to the one you normally at in? Which one did you normally eat in, the kitchen?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh in the kitchen, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would there be any time when you'd eat in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, no. You could go in the back room but they always used to have it in the kitchen then. Scullery. Used to go in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
She had a scullery you know. But - used to be baker in - in Market Street, he'd bake it - anybody could take their dinner over to the - in the big oven you know, wide oven what they
 used to bake with and - used to do all the cooking for nearly all the street. Take it over, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother have a cooking range or gas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh no, gas was - after that you know. Yes, gas was after that, yes. Yes. Simple one, you could boil ov
er the fire you see. Over the fire you'd boil a big - could boil up soup and like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What time of the day would breakfast be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh you see the - my - I used to have something before I went to work, six o'clock and we used to come home eight o'c
lock for one hour. Nine o'clock back again. One o'clock for dinner, back again. And leave work six o'clock. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So you'd come back for dinner would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes. Yes. Yes, one o'clock, yes. Yes, that's mostly - most of the time like that you know, 
most of them - had a few different jobs see always come home about one o'clock. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
What members of the family would be present for breakfast, would your father be home most nights and for breakfast or would he be away for days at a time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh -
 he might be gone - I come home from mill say eight o'clock, he might be gone off he work see, I don't know his time for his start you see, he'd be gone. Of course I wouldn't see him not 'til the day was ended like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother get everybody up for the first meal of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Well I don't think - I don't think like mother make - dad always get up first thing, he was up and - shouldn't have very much before us went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What kind of things would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Have a cup of tea that's all but
 - wait for breakfast time you see. It was pretty early to get anything you know, half past five in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So when would breakfast time be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Well I say us come home - us come home eight o'clock and - eight to nine and we got to go back work
 again nine o'clock. Say about half past eight or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What did you usually eat or drink for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I can't - quite remember that. Used to have porridge and one thing and another. Yes. Porridge, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 And just a cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have anything special on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh bit of joint and all that you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would you have eggs and bacon and things like that on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, I think so, yes. Eggs was cheaper for one thing and then - that was it 
you see, you could have it - have it cooked over the - baker, in an open stove. Used to warm it up with faggots of wood, they used to get it from Hembury in those days and - loads of wood and - he could put many dinners in that oven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 That would be mainly for the midday and evening meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
That was Sunday one, that's - only did it for Sunday you see with the - but - didn't charge you very much because you used to go there for bread and one thing and another you see. Very good of him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What would you eat for midday meals in the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh - maybe soup and different things you know. Can't remember all of it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How about the evening meal, would it be a hot meal or a cold meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 A cold one sometimes I expect most times. Yes. Couldn't have a cooked meal all day you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have a roast joint or something on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes, you had a roast joint on Sunday, yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would you eat that at midday or in the evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh midday Sundays, yes. That'd be - pro
per cooked meal like. You had to go a certain time over the bakers to get your dinner you see, used to be all - used to be several dinners - done there that day and used to - fetch yours from the - well just where the Co-op branch shop used to be, that's 
where the baker used to be, Market Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 This was mainly one baker or were there several doing this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
No. Oh I don't know about the bottom of the town but this one used to do that for you, and of course some - some of 'em did in the - got togeth
er and got - did get a - like the coal one you know, the coal - burnt - you know, burnt the coal and wood and one thing and another like. Yes. Come to think of it we did have one - iron - iron one, you know, they were iron ones like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother or father ever bake their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, I don't think they baked bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What about making jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Oh yes we did that - yes we - in those days many people used to - pickle - pickle stuff and one thing and another and make jams and all that for the - during the summer months. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How about bottling fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 They used to bottle, yes, like red cabbage and shallots and all like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did they ever make wine or home made medicines?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, I don't think mother did but
 - friends around used to come - come and bring some over you know. Yes. Some people used to go in for it a lot you know, all sorts, they go in for everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You hear a lot about this country cider around here don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes. Used to be in - in the pubs then there used to be a lot of cider. And there used to be a lot of cider drinkers in those days.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Farmers used to make it didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes? Farmers used to make it. Several pounds - what they call pounds - for making the cider in B
uckfastleigh in those days you know, there was, yes. I think it used to be about a penny a pint or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would you have to go to the pubs to get it, you couldn't go to the farmers and get some?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You maybe able to buy - if you wanted to buy it off the farmers, I think you could now you know. Yes. Get a small barrel of cider.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 It's all legal is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes, you could buy it off the farmers, oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you have any beer brewed or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your mother or father ever grow their own vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
I don't think we did so much, I think that I done it later but I don't know - but - every other - well every - you know practically every other one had a garden in those d
ays, yes, oh yes. Yes, there used to be pretty little gardens, weren't trying to be for what they could produce or anything. Yes. And there was a lot of allotments about in those days. Belonged to the firm, the Hamden firm, there was - allotments up Walla
f
ord Road there, and you see had - sixty or seventy allotments there. And - up the Old Totnes Road, all the Totnes Road there where you turn up - right up to Bigadon, used to be gardens there, allotments there. And - like Buckfastleight, they had plenty of
 
allotments. Oh there was plenty of allotments about in those days and practically every house had a bit of garden. Yes. I done a bit later on from - when I got about - thirteen year old I used to do a bit of gardening, had a garden over - Tweenaways but -
 that was - allotments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you ever buy any vegetables and fruit?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You could - yes, they used to come around with vegetables, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Who would come round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Some farmers and one thing and another, people used to come round certain - bags 
of potatoes and - cabbages and - in fact sometimes they bring - at the same time bring rabbits - rabbits along for sale you know, very cheap. Oh yes, they used to come round every Saturday. Well you could get plenty of vegetables in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you ever get dried vegetables or tinned vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, not in those days, no, no. No. It was all fresh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did your parents ever have any livestock like hens or pigs or goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No, we didn't have the - facilities but - many - used to b
e allowed to - you know, have pigs close at home in those days. Not the - like it is present day, got to be - sixty, seventy yards away from the - a dwelling. Used to - say twenty yards away you could have a pig then. They used to go in for it in those da
ys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Ordinary people used to have them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, ordinary, just ordinary people, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 What did they use the pigs for then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Sometimes they used to take 'em to the Co-op for sale, sometimes used to keep half of them themself, got them ha
nging up. Yes. Oh used to go a lot of that going. And fowls. Lot of 'em used to keep poultry there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 You didn't have any yourself in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 No. There was no room, no, we were between two houses you see. You - you want to be in the end house
 and want spare land for that job you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 How often a week would you say you ate meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh had some in the week, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would you have some meat every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Yes, practically so, yes, I think so. Yes. 'Course be - cheap in those day
s you see, well - well I said cheap but of course there was - as I say, the money was more value wasn't it. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Would it be tinned meat or fresh meat?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh fresh meat. 'Cos never seen no tinned meat - not tinned stuff in those days. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you ever get any extra meat from poaching, or did you hear of any poaching going on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Oh used to be a lot of - I didn't used to go - I never went rabbiting very much, I've done a bit too but - there used to be a lot of poaching in those days. 'C
ourse the - there was - plenty of rabbits about in those days. Yes. You could easy buy a cheap - you could buy a rabbit cheap in those days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did you get the rabbits from the farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Farmers and lot of poachers used to go - poaching you know. But I - every other house had a dog or a cat you know in those days, yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 So you'd often buy rabbits somebody else had poached then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Oh yes, sometimes, yes. But of course see - used to shout the odds who'd got the best dog and who's the best rabbitter and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Were there people going around trying to arrest people who poached rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
Well you see a policeman - he had his hands full, he couldn't - they'd watch 'em out of sight and one thing and another, they'd get - they'd get - we
ll of course a lot of the farmers would allow them to come, they'd go and ask the farmer, he's say, yes you can go - perhaps Saturday afternoon in certain fields not go outside those fields. And - they didn't want nothing back, he may take a couple of rab
bits back back to the farmer. But he was glad to get rid of 'em 'cos there was - you know, too many in the field eating corn and one thing and another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Did anyone poach chickens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 I daresay they did, yes, there used to be some ones about then, 'co
urse they'd no - some people they never went short because there was plenty about. I wouldn't do that myself but - it's been done you know. Yes. They always watch for the policeman, they know his time and - they go off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 Do you ever remember seeing your mother having less food so the family could have more
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16607039 WW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 
I don't - but - her would do. Her was one like that, might have done, yes. 'Cos you see when you're young - young like that, say up to - nine, ten years old you don't think a lot of notice what'
s going on do you, not 'til you get older. No. You live from day to day, you don't think about all these -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9923787 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1402753\charrsid5841043 She'd probably try and not make it known anyway wouldn't she?
